    "For all feature maps φ:X → R d, ψ: Z → R d, we have L d (φ, ψ) ≥ ∥T -T d ∥ 2 HS = i>d σ 2 i,where equality holds if and only ifT d (φ, ψ) = T d, in which case H φ,d = V d, H ψ,d = U d. T d is the rank-d truncation of T introduced in Section 2.While the Eckart-Young-Mirsky objective in Eq.",
    "( 6) offers a clean objective to learn spectral features, it appears impractical due to the unknown nature of the operator T. However, this objective admits an equivalent formulation as a spectral contrastive learning loss [37]:L d (φ, ψ) = E X E Z (φ(X) T ψ(Z)) 2 -2E X,Z [φ(X) T ψ(Z)] + ∥T ∥ 2 HS,(7)where the last term is independent of (φ, ψ).",
    "We provide a proof of this equivalence in Appendix C.3.The population loss can be estimated from samplesDm = {(x i, zi)} m i=1 as Ld (φ, ψ).",
    "= 1 m(m -1) i̸ =j (φ(x i) T ψ(z j)) 2 - 2 m m i=1 φ(x i) T ψ(z i).",
    "(8)The spectral contrastive loss is the basis of the recent algorithm proposed in [36], where φ and ψ are parametrized by neural networks and optimized via stochastic gradient descent."
  ],
